4:["$","h3","h3-6",{"children":"1801: Joseph-Marie Jacquard's Programmable Loom"}]
5:["$","p","p-7",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Jacquard loom uses punched cards to control thread selection patterns.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The first programmable manufacturing machine; patterns encoded externally, interpreted mechanically.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Connection"}],": Punched cards remained the primary computer input method until the 1970s."]}]
6:["$","h3","h3-7",{"children":"1837: Charles Babbage & Ada Lovelace's Analytical Engine"}]
7:["$","p","p-8",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Babbage designs a mechanical general-purpose computer. Ada Lovelace publishes the first algorithm intended to be carried out by such a machine (calculating Bernoulli numbers).\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": The conceptual birth of software separating from hardware. Lovelace recognized that the machine could manipulate any symbols (like music or logic), not just numbers, forecasting the true nature of modern computing."]}]
8:["$","h3","h3-8",{"children":"1861-1876: Telegraph & Early Electrical Automation"}]
9:["$","p","p-9",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": Telegraph systems use electrical signals for long-distance communication; relay circuits enable switching.",["$","br","br-0",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": Introduces electrical actuation and logical switching.",["$","br","br-1",{}],"\n",["$","strong","strong-2",{"children":"Modern Parallel"}],": Foundation of digital logic and electrical control systems."]}]
a:["$","h3","h3-9",{"children":"1868: James Clerk Maxwell's \"On Governors\""}]
b:["$","p","p-10",{"children":[["$","strong","strong-0",{"children":"Event"}],": The brilliant physicist publishes a paper analyzing the mathematical stability of Watt's centrifugal governor using differential equations.\n",["$","strong","strong-1",{"children":"Significance"}],": This is widely considered the true, formal birth of Control Theory as an academic and mathematical discipline. He proved mathematically ",["$","em","em-0",{"children":"why"}]," and ",["$","em","em-1",{"children":"when"}]," a feedback system becomes unstable (hunting or oscillating), moving automation from trial-and-error engineering into rigorous mathematics."]}]
